THE Goſpel exceeds the Law, not only in an accidental or adventitious, but alſo an intrinſick Glory. The Law was not only made glorious in the Eyes of the Children of Iſrael, by the dignity of the Perſon and luſtre on the face of Moſes, by whom it came, and the manner of its delivery, but it was glorious in it ſelf; being a Revelation from GOD of his Excellencies to his Creatures, and his Will concerning them: But the Goſpel is more glorious in it ſelf, being a clearer, and more compleat Revelation of GOD'S Glory. This is hinted by the Apoſtle in our Context, where he is ſhewing how the Goſpel exceeds the Law in Glory, v. 18. But we all with open face, beholding as in a Glaſs the Glory of the Lord. Moſes put a Vail over his Face, when he came down from the Mount, that ſo all the Glory of his Countenance might not be ſeen, might not this repreſent GOD'S concealing from the Jewiſh People much of his Glory, which was afterwards to be manifeſted? v. 13. Moſes put a Vail over his face, that the Children of Iſrael could not ſtedfaſtly look to the end of that which is aboliſhed. They had but an obſcure View of the Myſtery of CHRIST, which was vailed under the Types and Shadows of the Ceremonial Law; like as the Glory on the face of Moſes was vailed. v. 14 But their Minds were blinded: for until this day remaineth the ſame vail untaken away, in the reading of the Old Teſtament: which vail is done away in Chriſt. The vail of outward Shadows and Types was removed, by Chriſt's coming into the World: for then the Prefigurations, Propheſies and Promiſes of the Meſſiah were fulfilled, and the Glory of GOD in our Redemption by Chriſt was to be clearly ſeen: But the vail of ſpiritual Blindneſs on the Minds and Hearts of the Jews, which was alſo myſtically
ſignified by the Vail upon the face of Moſes, remains to this day in their reading the Old Teſtament, which hinders them from diſcovering the Meſſiah to be already come, and that the Types and Propheſies are accompliſhed in him. But we all with open face, all we who believe have the Vail removed from us, ſo that with open face we behold the Glory of the Lord as in a Glaſs, i. e. in the Goſpel, which is as a Glaſs, not a Perſpective thro' which things afar off are darkly ſeen, but a Looking-glaſs fully repreſenting the face as near. The Glory of the Lord, which was vail'd and cover'd under the Types and Shadows of the Law, is now by the Goſpel clearly revealed. And how Chriſtians do in the Goſpel, as it is a Glaſs, ſee the Glory of GOD, the Apoſtle telleth us, 2 Cor. 4.6. For GOD who Commanded the light to ſhine out of darkneſs, hath ſhined in our 〈◊〉 , to give the light of the knowledge of the glory of GOD, in face of Jeſus Chriſt. By the face of Jeſus Chriſt, in which the Glory of GOD is ſeen, the Apoſtle ſeems to allude to that divine Luſtre with which the Face of Moſes ſhone, when he came down from Mount Sinai: So that his meaning may be this, That as the Children of Iſrael with their bodily Eyes ſaw ſomething of GOD'S Glory ſhining in the Face of Moſes; ſo they the Diſciples of our Saviour, did more clearly with the Eyes of their enlightned Underſtandings behold the divine Glory in Jeſus Chriſt, whoſe Face the Glaſs of the Goſpel repreſented to them. Chriſt is the brightneſs of God's Glory, and the expreſs Image of his Perſon. There is no Perfection in GOD, which is not in Chriſt, for Chriſt is GOD. And in that Glaſs wherein we ſee the Face of Chriſt who is thus the Image of GOD, we behold the Glory of GOD; and in the Goſpel of Jeſus Chriſt is more clearly revealed. By the Law Men might diſcern, as it were GOD'S Back-parts. As He ſaid unto Moſes, who beſeeched the LORD to ſhew him his Glory, Exod. 33.23. Thou ſhalt ſee my back-parts: but my Face ſhall not be ſeen: But in the Goſpel we may ſee the Face of Jeſus Chriſt, and ſo the Face of GOD;
for CHRIST is the adequate and eſſential Image of GOD. The knowledge of Chriſt, and ſo of GOD'S Glory, which could be obtain'd by the Writings of Moſes and the Prophets, was ſmall, compar'd with that which the Goſpel affords; and did not the New Teſtament expound the Old, wou'd not the Vail on the face of Moſes, as to us, remain untaken away.

IT is true, that many who remain in their natural Condition, do appear righteous in the eye of the World;
but they are not ſo in the ſight of GOD: They may be outwardly clean; may waſh the out-ſide of the Cup and Platter, and garniſh the Sepulchre with ſpecious ſhews of Devotion; but are inwardly defiled, full of all Uncleanneſs, ſpiritual Putrefaction, Hypocriſy and Iniquity, Luke 16.15. He ſaid unto them, Ye are they which juſtifie your ſelves before men; but God knoweth your hearts: for that which is highly eſteemed amongſt men, is abomintion in the ſight of God. Further, As all unconverted Sinners are, in reſpect of the Pollution of their Nature, in ſpiritual Sodom, ſo many of them may be fitly ſaid to be ſo, in regard of the actual Defilements which they wallow in. The Soil of corrupt Nature yieldeth the Fruits of Sodom, Deut. 32.32. Their vine is of the vine of Sodom, and of the fields of Gomorrah: their grapes are grapes of gall, their cluſters are bitter. Such are addreſſed as Inhabitants of Sodom & Gomorrah, who practis'd the Sins which abounded there, Iſa. 1.10. Hear the word of the Lord, ye rulers of Sodom; give ear unto the law of our God, ye people of Gomorrah. The Rulers and People of Iſrael had made themſelves in reſpect of Sin, like thoſe of Sodom and Gomorrah, therefore the faithful Prophet gave them this Title: They deſerved no better. Rome is called Sodom for it's reſembling it in Whordom, and all filthineſs both of Fleſh and Spirit, Rev. 11.8. Their dead bodies ſhall lie in the ſtreet of the great 〈◊〉 , which ſpiritually is called Sodom. What Multitudes are there who live in the Practice of the abominable Sins of Sodom, Pride, fulneſs of Bread, (i. e. Exceſs in Meats and Drinks,) abundance of Idleneſs, Uncharitableneſs and Oppreſſion? How many, like the People of Sodom, give themſelves over unto Laciviouſneſs, to work all Uncleanneſs with greedineſs? How many declare their Sin as Sodom, and hide it not? Their Foreheads are ſteel'd with Impudence, they boaſt of their Wickedneſs, and glory in their Shame. How wretchedly ſecure are the moſt in the State of Nature, as the People were in Sodom? They are ſetled on their filthy Lees, quiet & undiſturb'd
in their Sins, giving themſelves up wholly to ſecular Buſineſs, and ſenſual Delights. As it was in the days of Lot; they did eat, they drank, they bought, they ſold, they planted, they builded, not fearing Deſtruction till it was brought upon them: Even ſo it is alſo in the days of the Son of Man.
